6":"1366","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1266":"1266","1320":"1320","after 1350":"after 1350","after 1333":"after 1333","1318":"1318","about 1296":"about 1296","1306":"1306","Næsbyholm, Skåne":"Næsbyholm, Suså, Storstrøm, Denmark","Näsbyholm Castle, Skurup, Skåne, Sweden":"Skurup, Skåne, Sweden","Lund, Skåne, Sweden":"Lund, Skåne, Sweden","Ganslose, Schleswig-Holstein, Germany":"Schleswig-Holstein, Germany","Lund domkirke, Lund, Skåne, Sweden":"Lund, Lund, Skåne, Sweden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Galen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch (<b>Van Galen</b>): habitational name, probably from the German town of Gahlen in North Rhine-Westphalia, or perhaps from the village Gaal in the province of North Brabant.","English (Cambridgeshire and Essex): variant of   Galyon   or   Gallon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Galyon","meanings":["English: variant of   Gallion  . This form of the surname has died out in Britain. Compare   Galyan   and   Galyen  ."]}]},{"name":"Peder","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jensen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is probably a variant of <i>Janson</i> ‘son of Jan’, a medieval form of   John ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357047,"age":6,"year":"1266","julianDay":2183458,"description":"King Valdemar overthrown by brothers.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1702075,"age":46,"year":"1306","julianDay":2198067,"title":"The Hatuna Games","description":"A conflict on September 29, 1306, between Birger, King of Sweden, and his brothers, the dukes Eric Magnusson and Valdemar Magnusson is known as The Hatuna Games. The brothers arrived to a party late in the night at King Birger's estate. The dukes captured and imprisoned Birger and his wife in Nykoping Castle's dungeon. Duke Eric then gained power over Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357048,"age":58,"year":"1318","julianDay":2202450,"description":"Peasants revolted against King.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357049,"age":63,"year":"1323","julianDay":2204276,"description":"Sweden and Russia establish border.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1357050,"age":90,"year":"1350","julianDay":2214138,"description":"Black Death killed one-third of population.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Peder Jensen Galen was born about 1260, in Skurup, Skåne, Sweden as the son of Jens Nielsen Galen and Christine Petersdatter. He married Gräfin Regitze von Gleichen-Tonna. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 16 April 1355, in Lund, Skåne, Sweden, at the age of 96, and was buried in Lund, Lund, Skåne, Sweden."},"et":{"about 1260–16 April 1355":"umbes 1260–16. aprill 1355","1260–1355":"1260–1355","1282–1351":"1282–1351","1290–1335":"1290–1335","1300–1366":"1300–1366","–Female":"Surnud","1245–1333":"1245–1333","1296–1350":"1296–1350","–1320":"–1320","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","16 April 1355":"16. aprill 1355","1296":"1296","1351":"1351","1350":"1350","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1335":